WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.534 --> 00:00:04.501
[ WHIRRING ]

00:00:04.501 --> 00:00:06.601
[ SUSPENSEFUL MUSIC PLAYS ]

00:00:06.601 --> 00:00:09.868
Narrator:
MAY 1, 2014.

00:00:09.868 --> 00:00:13.400
A NASA PLANE IS MONITORING
ICE THICKNESS OVER GREENLAND,

00:00:13.400 --> 00:00:16.601
AN ARCTIC WILDERNESS MORE THAN
TWICE THE SIZE OF TEXAS.

00:00:16.601 --> 00:00:18.701
[ WHIRRING ]

00:00:18.701 --> 00:00:22.934
BELOW THEM, THE CREW NOTICES
SOMETHING UNUSUAL.

00:00:22.934 --> 00:00:27.734
YOU HAVE THIS WIDE EXPANSE,
BUT THEN THERE'S AN OBJECT.

00:00:27.734 --> 00:00:30.701
♪♪

00:00:30.701 --> 00:00:35.701
IT APPEARS TO BE THIS BLACKENED
ARM COMING OUT OF THE ICE.

00:00:35.701 --> 00:00:39.167
♪♪

00:00:39.167 --> 00:00:42.534
Narrator:
IMAGE ANALYST MARK D'ANTONIO
DIALS UP THE MAGNIFICATION

00:00:42.534 --> 00:00:45.634
AND DISCOVERS
SOMETHING DISTURBING.

00:00:45.634 --> 00:00:49.667
YOU CAN SEE A LITTLE BIT MORE
DETAIL ABOUT WHAT WE HAVE HERE.

00:00:49.667 --> 00:00:52.334
THIS IS ACTUALLY
AN AIRCRAFT WING

00:00:52.334 --> 00:00:54.467
AND PART OF
AN AIRCRAFT FUSELAGE.

00:00:54.467 --> 00:00:56.501
♪♪

00:00:56.501 --> 00:00:59.133
THE IDEA OF BEING IN A PLANE
CRASH IS SCARY ENOUGH,

00:00:59.133 --> 00:01:02.300
BUT THEN IMAGINING CRASHING
IN A PLACE LIKE THIS,

00:01:02.300 --> 00:01:05.000
THAT'S SO DESOLATE,
SO REMOTE,

00:01:05.000 --> 00:01:08.868
THAT'S GOT TO BE ONE OF THE MOST
FRIGHTENING THINGS IMAGINABLE.

00:01:08.868 --> 00:01:11.267
Narrator:
BUT NOT AS FRIGHTENING
AS WHAT THE TEAM SPOTS

00:01:11.267 --> 00:01:14.567
IN THE SNOW NEXT TO THE PLANE.

00:01:14.567 --> 00:01:18.801
THESE ARE BIG ANIMAL TRACKS
AND, IN THIS PART OF GREENLAND,

00:01:18.801 --> 00:01:21.868
THERE'S ONLY ONE THING
THAT COULD MAKE THEM --

00:01:21.868 --> 00:01:23.033
POLAR BEARS.

00:01:23.033 --> 00:01:25.701
♪♪

00:01:25.701 --> 00:01:27.434
Narrator:
POLAR BEARS CAN CONSUME

00:01:27.434 --> 00:01:31.200
OVER 300 POUNDS OF MEAT
IN A SINGLE SITTING.

00:01:31.200 --> 00:01:34.667
THAT'S ROUGHLY 1.5 PILOTS.

00:01:34.667 --> 00:01:37.367
IF YOU FIND YOURSELF
IN THIS PART OF THE WORLD,

00:01:37.367 --> 00:01:40.100
ESPECIALLY IF YOU
ARE SICK OR INJURED,

00:01:40.100 --> 00:01:42.367
YOU ARE NOW PART
OF THE FOOD CHAIN,

00:01:42.367 --> 00:01:44.033
AND NOT AT THE TOP.

00:01:44.033 --> 00:01:46.267
♪♪

00:01:46.267 --> 00:01:48.234
Narrator:
AVIATION RECORDS REVEAL
THAT THERE HAVE BEEN

00:01:48.234 --> 00:01:52.934
NO LARGE PLANE CRASHES
IN THIS AREA FOR DECADES.

00:01:52.934 --> 00:01:55.100
A SEARCH OF WORLD WAR II
ACCIDENTS

00:01:55.100 --> 00:01:57.300
YIELDS A POSSIBLE CLUE.

00:01:57.300 --> 00:02:00.367
THERE WAS A B-17 THAT WAS
DISPATCHED DURING WORLD WAR II,

00:02:00.367 --> 00:02:04.467
LOOKING FOR A CARGO PLANE
THAT WENT MISSING.

00:02:04.467 --> 00:02:08.100
THAT B-17 CRASHED
IN THIS GENERAL AREA.

00:02:08.100 --> 00:02:10.000
Baker:
COULD THIS BE IT?

00:02:10.000 --> 00:02:12.100
IS THIS THE PLANE
THAT WENT DOWN?

00:02:12.100 --> 00:02:15.167
♪♪

00:02:15.167 --> 00:02:17.901
Narrator:
ON NOVEMBER 9, 1942,

00:02:17.901 --> 00:02:21.901
A B-17 FLYING FORTRESS TAKES OFF
FROM ONE OF THE U.S. MILITARY'S

00:02:21.901 --> 00:02:24.267
WORLD WAR II AIR BASES
IN GREENLAND,

00:02:24.267 --> 00:02:28.000
TO SEARCH FOR A CARGO PLANE
THAT CRASHED FOUR DAYS EARLIER.

00:02:28.000 --> 00:02:29.467
♪♪

00:02:29.467 --> 00:02:33.400
BUT THE B-17 ALSO CRASHES.

00:02:33.400 --> 00:02:36.534
THE PLANE CRASHES,
BUT IT'S A CONTROLLED CRASH

00:02:36.534 --> 00:02:39.167
AND THE NINE CREWMEN SURVIVE.

00:02:39.167 --> 00:02:40.667
♪♪

00:02:40.667 --> 00:02:43.033
Narrator:
THE MILITARY DISPATCHES
A SEAPLANE,

00:02:43.033 --> 00:02:45.067
WHICH RESCUES TWO
OF THE STRANDED CREWMEN

00:02:45.067 --> 00:02:48.567
BEFORE RETURNING
TO PICK UP ONE MORE.

00:02:48.567 --> 00:02:50.667
AND THEN YOU'RE NOT GONNA
BELIEVE WHAT HAPPENS.

00:02:50.667 --> 00:02:52.400
THAT PLANE THEN CRASHES

00:02:52.400 --> 00:02:54.868
AND ALL THREE MEN
ONBOARD ARE KILLED.

00:02:54.868 --> 00:02:56.701
♪♪

00:02:56.701 --> 00:02:57.834
Narrator:
OVER THE FOLLOWING WEEKS,

00:02:57.834 --> 00:02:59.901
THE MILITARY
LAUNCHES SEVERAL ATTEMPTS

00:02:59.901 --> 00:03:03.334
TO RESCUE THE REMAINING
STRANDED AIRMEN.

00:03:03.334 --> 00:03:06.767
ALL FAIL.

00:03:06.767 --> 00:03:09.334
THE SIX CREW MEMBERS
AND A RESCUE-SLED DRIVER

00:03:09.334 --> 00:03:11.000
WHO HAD MANAGED TO REACH THEM

00:03:11.000 --> 00:03:13.334
MUST FACE THE ONSLAUGHT
OF AN ARCTIC WINTER

00:03:13.334 --> 00:03:17.367
PROTECTED ONLY BY THE WRECKED
FUSELAGE OF THEIR B-17.

00:03:17.367 --> 00:03:18.868
[ WIND BLOWING ]

00:03:18.868 --> 00:03:21.667
THEY'RE THERE
FOR AN ENTIRE MONTH.

00:03:21.667 --> 00:03:25.501
NOW, WHAT'S IT LIKE BEING,
FOR A MONTH, ON THE ARCTIC?

00:03:25.501 --> 00:03:26.901
IT'S HELL.

00:03:26.901 --> 00:03:28.934
Pappalardo:
IT'S -40°.

00:03:28.934 --> 00:03:30.767
YOU ARE IN A WORLD OF HURT.

00:03:30.767 --> 00:03:34.067
ONE OF THE CREW MEMBERS DEVELOPS
GANGRENE IN BOTH HIS FEET

00:03:34.067 --> 00:03:38.701
AND THEY ACTUALLY FALL OFF
INSIDE HIS BOOTS.

00:03:38.701 --> 00:03:41.734
Narrator:
TORMENTED BY HUNGER,
FROSTBITE, AND DELIRIUM,

00:03:41.734 --> 00:03:44.467
ON JANUARY 4, 1943,

00:03:44.467 --> 00:03:45.968
THE TEAM SPLITS UP.

00:03:45.968 --> 00:03:47.934
♪♪

00:03:47.934 --> 00:03:51.834
A MONTH LATER, A SEARCH TEAM
FINDS THREE OF THEM ALIVE

00:03:51.834 --> 00:03:53.234
AND, ON MARCH 18th,

00:03:53.234 --> 00:03:57.000
[ DOGS BARKING ]
AFTER 133 DAYS ALONE ON THE ICE,

00:03:57.000 --> 00:03:59.834
THE REMAINING CREW
FIND SANCTUARY.

00:03:59.834 --> 00:04:02.934
THEIR ABSOLUTELY
REMARKABLE SURVIVAL

00:04:02.934 --> 00:04:05.701
IS ONE OF THE GREAT
ENDURANCE STORIES OF ALL TIME.

00:04:05.701 --> 00:04:07.667
♪♪

00:04:07.667 --> 00:04:10.100
Narrator:
ANALYSTS CONSIDER
IF THE IMAGE HAS CAPTURED

00:04:10.100 --> 00:04:15.400
THE CREW'S WRECKED PLANE LOCKED
IN THE ICE FOR OVER 70 YEARS.

00:04:15.400 --> 00:04:18.300
YET, WHEN D'ANTONIO
CAREFULLY STUDIES ITS WING,

00:04:18.300 --> 00:04:20.834
HE CASTS DOUBT ON THIS IDEA.

00:04:20.834 --> 00:04:23.000
WHEN YOU LOOK AT THE SIZE
OF THE WINGSPAN,

00:04:23.000 --> 00:04:27.367
FROM WING TIP TO WING TIP,
THIS DISTANCE IS ABOUT 140 FEET.

00:04:27.367 --> 00:04:30.868
THAT'S TOO LARGE FOR A B-17.

00:04:30.868 --> 00:04:33.868
I WOULD BANK ON THIS BEING
A B-29 SUPERFORTRESS CRASH.

00:04:33.868 --> 00:04:38.033
[ ENGINE ROARS ]

00:04:38.033 --> 00:04:40.868
Narrator:
AVIATION JOURNALIST
JOE PAPPALARDO CONFIRMS

00:04:40.868 --> 00:04:45.334
THAT B-29 SUPERFORTRESSES MADE
FREQUENT FLIGHTS OVER GREENLAND

00:04:45.334 --> 00:04:49.667
AS PART OF THE UNITED STATES'S
COLD WAR SURVEILLANCE CAMPAIGN.

00:04:49.667 --> 00:04:52.534
THEY WERE DUBBED FERRET FLIGHTS
BECAUSE THEY WERE TRYING

00:04:52.534 --> 00:04:54.968
TO FERRET OUT INFORMATION
ABOUT THE SOVIET UNION

00:04:54.968 --> 00:04:58.100
AND ALL OF THEIR
CLANDESTINE AIRFIELDS.

00:04:58.100 --> 00:05:01.033
Narrator:
PAPPALARDO LEARNS
THAT, IN 1947,

00:05:01.033 --> 00:05:04.133
ONE OF THESE SUPERFORTRESSES,
CALLED THE KEE BIRD,

00:05:04.133 --> 00:05:06.634
CRASHES NEAR THE SITE
IN THE AERIAL IMAGE.

00:05:06.634 --> 00:05:08.567
♪♪

00:05:08.567 --> 00:05:11.434
THIS ELEVEN-MAN CREW
HITS A VERY BAD STORM.

00:05:11.434 --> 00:05:13.567
[ SUSPENSEFUL MUSIC CLIMBS ]

00:05:13.567 --> 00:05:17.234
THE B-29 COMES DOWN,
BUT EVERYONE ON BOARD SURVIVES.

00:05:17.234 --> 00:05:18.701
♪♪

00:05:18.701 --> 00:05:22.834
Narrator: THE B-29 REMAINS
UNTOUCHED FOR 47 YEARS.

00:05:22.834 --> 00:05:25.133
♪♪

00:05:25.133 --> 00:05:29.934
IN 1994, A TEAM OF ENGINEERS
ARRIVE AT THE CRASH SITE,

00:05:29.934 --> 00:05:32.267
DETERMINED TO MAKE HER
AIRWORTHY AGAIN,

00:05:32.267 --> 00:05:36.901
AND SPEND MONTHS FITTING NEW
ENGINES, PROPELLERS, AND WHEELS.

00:05:36.901 --> 00:05:39.734
GREAT IDEA, I SUPPOSE.
[laughs]

00:05:39.734 --> 00:05:41.634
I DON'T KNOW THAT I'D WANT
TO SPEND 10 MONTHS

00:05:41.634 --> 00:05:45.300
IN THOSE CONDITIONS,
REKITTING ENGINES ON A B-29,

00:05:45.300 --> 00:05:46.467
BUT THAT'S WHAT THEY DID.

00:05:46.467 --> 00:05:47.968
♪♪

00:05:47.968 --> 00:05:50.868
Narrator:
ON MAY 21, 1995,

00:05:50.868 --> 00:05:54.000
THE TEAM FIRES UP
THE SUPERFORTRESS' ENGINES

00:05:54.000 --> 00:05:55.968
AND SHE PREPARES
TO TAKE TO THE SKIES

00:05:55.968 --> 00:05:58.601
FOR THE FIRST TIME
IN HALF A CENTURY.

00:05:58.601 --> 00:06:00.334
[ EXPLOSION ]

00:06:00.334 --> 00:06:03.734
BUT THEN, A FUEL LEAK
IN THE FUSELAGE STARTS A FIRE

00:06:03.734 --> 00:06:08.133
THAT QUICKLY ENGULFS THE PLANE,
DESTROYING IT IN MINUTES.

00:06:08.133 --> 00:06:09.501
D'Antonio:
THAT HAD TO BE HEART-WRENCHING.

00:06:09.501 --> 00:06:12.067
I CAN'T EVEN IMAGINE
WHAT THEY FELT.

00:06:12.067 --> 00:06:15.501
Baker:
IT'S LIKE GREENLAND
MIGHT BE CURSED, RIGHT?

00:06:15.501 --> 00:06:17.100
I MEAN, YOU COULDN'T
WRITE THAT ENDING.

00:06:17.100 --> 00:06:19.234
♪♪

00:06:19.234 --> 00:06:23.033
Narrator:
TODAY, THE KEE BIRD REMAINS
LOCKED IN THE GREENLAND ICE,

00:06:23.033 --> 00:06:27.968
A HAUNTING RELIC OF THE
COLD WAR, FROZEN IN TIME.

00:06:27.968 --> 00:06:31.200
Walters:
IN A WAY, I THINK IT'S FITTING
THAT SHE DIDN'T FLY OFF.

00:06:31.200 --> 00:06:33.968
SHE'S LIKE A MEMORIAL
TO ALL THOSE BRAVE MEN

00:06:33.968 --> 00:06:36.400
WHO FLEW THOSE MISSIONS
OVER THAT PART OF THE WORLD.

00:06:36.400 --> 00:06:39.934
♪♪

